<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="13" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="13">
Prior to this study, dead shells of 
<taxonomicName class="Bivalvia" family="Vesicomyidae" genus="Pliocardia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pliocardia donacia" order="Venerida" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="donacia">Pliocardia donacia</taxonomicName>
were identified in Pacific Colombia at depths between 272 and 295 m (
<bibRefCitation author="Gracia, A" journalOrPublisher="Marine Biodiversity Records" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" pagination="1 - 15" title="New records of soft bottom bivalves (Mollusca) inhabiting the northern Pacific Ocean of Colombia." url="https://doi.org/10.1017/S1755267214000566" volume="7" year="2014">Gracia and Valentich-Scott 2014</bibRefCitation>
). The present collection in southern Colombia yielded one live specimen and two empty valves, suggesting that the species inhabits both the northern and southern Colombian Pacific. Further, the bathymetric limit of the species is extended to 656 m in the Colombian Pacific. Many generic uncertainties exist within the family 
<taxonomicName family="Vesicomyidae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" rank="family">Vesicomyidae</taxonomicName>
. Thus, we follow 
<bibRefCitation pageId="0" pageNumber="13">Coan and Valentich-Scott (2012)</bibRefCitation>
in their tentative placement of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. donacia" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" rank="species" species="donacia">P. donacia</taxonomicName>
within the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Bivalvia" family="Vesicomyidae" genus="Pliocardia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pliocardia" order="Venerida" pageId="0" pageNumber="13" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Pliocardia</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
